===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Having given oneself up to [[vice]]; [[immoral]]; [[extremely]] wicked, or [[sinning]] without restraint; [[irreclaimably]] wicked. {{defdate|First attested from 1350 to 1470}}<ref name =SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>
#* '''1876''', Alexander Davidson, ''A Complete History of Illinois from 1673 to 1884'' (page 232)
#*: Such immunity to offenders offered a safe asylum to the vilest and most '''abandoned''' scoundrels.
# No longer maintained by its former owners, residents{{,}} or caretakers; [[forsaken]], [[deserted]]. {{defdate|Late 15th century}}<ref name =SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|author=Thomson|passage={{...}} your '''abandoned''' streams {{...}}}}
# Free from constraint; [[uninhibited]]. {{defdate|Late 17th century}}<ref name =SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1919|author=[[w:William Somerset Maugham|W. Somerset Maugham]]|title=[[w:The Moon and Sixpence|The Moon and Sixpence]]|chapter=11|passage=Everything was dirty and [[shabby]]. There was no sign of the '''abandoned''' luxury that Colonel MacAndrew had so confidently described.}}
# {{lb|en|geology}} No longer being acted upon by the geologic forces that formed it.

